I call BS and overhype. With all the scientific computing and HPC tools and libraries available today 35,000 times faster implies they entire sector has added nothing of value over the last 25 years. numbas, numpy and cython actually do impressively well on a wide selection of benchmarks.35,000 times, i.e. reducing a 9 hour 40 minute to a 1 second execution time, is simply a case of writing terrible Python code to begin with (e.g. Recursive Fibonacci, i.e. the worst possible way to calculate any simple number sequence compared to say, a for loop and a temporary variable), an end of lifed version of Python, and/or misleading benchmarks. I've never before come across an example where even rewriting in assembly improved any properly written code, by a factor of 35,000. OK vanilla CPython is single threaded, so I'll believe a factor of 10 improvement over badly written Python code is possible, plus on some incredibly niche problem that is so amazingly parallelisable you can throw 3,500 cores at it. But that's just cherry picking, i.e. an aforementioned misleading benchmark.

I'm not convinced. In the example, the dot product would normally be done with a highly optimized library like PyTorch which uses C under the hood anyway. Also, python is popular because it's so simple, so I don't think introducing low level concepts will be more than a niche thing. Cython already does this too.The direction I see is a smart AI compiler where you input Python or plain text and it does the optimization automatically. I regularly do this now with ChatGPT to parallelize/optimize my code. If Mojo is to become popular, it would likely need to be paired with automatic AI suggestions.

Seems quite disingenuous for them to quote performance gains against naively doing a matrix product in pure python nested for loops (plus a bunch of oop baggage for no apparent reason, not sure if that adds anything more)You can get a 300x improvement (on this tablet, YMMV) over their original pure python code just by using np.matmul which any vaguely normal person using python is doing just because it's far easier to write!No doubt further fairly dramatic gains could be found through use of numba decorators, which will jit compile and parallelize functions with llvm.Other options for low effort python speed increases exist. The comparison point needs to be against those sort of low effort boosts.

1) (MODULARIZACAO) Objetivo: Definir e executar modulos (com retorno)Elaborar um programa em Python que contenha dois modulos definidos (alem do corpo principal), ambos com retorno de valor. O programa recebe os coeficientes (numeros reais) de uma equacao de 2o grau, calcula (em um dos modulos) o valor de delta e imprime esse valor. Caso o valor de delta seja igual a zero, havera o calculo (outro modulo) do valor da raiz, que tambem devera ser impressa. As entradas de valores e as impressoes sao feitas sempre no corpo principal.Me ajudar!!!

Esse codigo que criou nao respeita a ordem e nem numeros unicos, se a ordem das lista forem alteradas. Ou seja, nao e eficiente.OBS: deixo a correcao do codigo no final.a = [1, 2, 3, 4]b = [1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]c = [3, 3, 6, 8, 3, 9, 10] > fica de olho no 3 do lado 8.Nesse codigo que o rapaz apresentou, se fizer uma alteracao nas listas nao respeitando a ordem, retorna os valores: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 3, 9, 10]Esse codigo nao funciona estavelmente na maioria das coisas que for aplicado.Segue o codigo dele para testarem:from heapq import mergedef unique(*it): values, previous, = merge(*it), merge(*it) yield next(values) yield from (v for v, p in zip(values, previous) if p != v)a = [1, 2, 3, 4]b = [1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]c = [3, 3, 6, 8, 3, 9, 10]unicos = unique(a, b, c)for v in unicos: print(v, end=' ')Aqui e um codigo que possui memoria constante, tempo de execucao linear, respeita a ordem e tem elementos unicos:OBS: bem dificil alguem conseguir fazer um codigo desse sem bugs ou falhas - tao facil de entender, viu...def uniq(lst): ord = set() for v in lst: if v not in ord: ord.add(v) lst = list(ord) return lsta = [1, 2, 11, 3, 4]b = [11, 3, 5, 4, 5, 5, 6, 7]c = [3, 3, 6, 8, 3, 9, 4, 6, 10]s = uniq(a + b + c)print(s)

fiz uma implementacao do merge que ja retorna os valores unicos, sem a biblioteca. A idea e baseada no algoritmo mergeSort:complexidade: O(n*m)n = tamanho do maior arraym = numero de arraysfrom math import infdef merge(*arrays): pointers = [0] * len(arrays) result = [] ended=False while not ended: min_value = min([arrays[i][pointers[i]] if pointers[i] < len(arrays[i]) else inf for i in range(len(arrays))]) pointers = [pointers[i] + 1 if pointers[i] < len(arrays[i]) and arrays[i][pointers[i]] == min_value else pointers[i] for i in range(len(arrays))] ended = min([pointers[i] == len(arrays[i]) for i in range(len(arrays))]) == True result.append(min_value) return resulta = [1, 2, 3, 4]b = [1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]c = [3, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 10001]print(merge(a, b, c))

No linux eu tenho experiencia em distros baseadas em Debian (Ubuntu e Mint). Para realizar o mesmo que foi feito no video e preciso saber qual o file manager em uso pelo sistema. No Mint ele se chama Nemo. Para adicionar novos itens e comandos no context menu dele e necessario criar um arquivo de texto para cada item na pasta: ~/.local/share/nemo/actions. O nome do arquivo por padrao tem que terminar com '.nemo_action'. Existe um botao chamado `More info` nessa pasta que gera um exemplo de sintaxe e estrutura desse arquivo (https://forums.linuxmint.com/viewtopic.php?t=283851). No caso do Ubuntu, se o file manager for o Nautilus e possivel instalar o nautilus-actions (sudo apt-get install nautilus-actions -y). Essa aplicacao tem uma GUI que facilita toda a operacao (https://askubuntu.com/questions/88480/adding-extra-options-to-right-click-menu). Ainda como uma outra opcao para o Mint, e possivel substituir o Nemo pelo Nautilus e instalar o nautilus-actions.

O programa deve calcular e imprimir: * O custo total para cada consumidor * O total de consumo para os tres tipos de consumidor * A media de consumo dos tipos 1 e 2

Solucao pra quem precisa de ajuda:n = input('digite algo: ')if n.isupper(): print(f'{n} e todo maiusculo.')else: print(f'{n} nao e todo maiusculo')if n.isalnum(): print(f'{n} e alfanumerico(e composto de letras e numeros)')else: print(f'{n} nao e alfanumerico(composto de letras ou numeros)')if n.isalpha(): print(f'{n} e composto somente por letras')else: print(f'{n} nao e composto apenas por letras')if n.isnumeric(): print(f'{n} e numerico(composto apenas por numeros)')else: print(f'{n} nao e numerico(composto apenas por numeros)')if n.isdigit(): print(f'{n} e um digito')else: print(f'{n} nao e um digito')if n.isdecimal(): print(f'{n} e um decimal')else: print(f'{n} nao e um decimal')if n.isidentifier(): print(f'{n} e um valido identificador de codigo')else: print(f'{n} nao e um valido identificador de codigo')if n.islower(): print(f'{n} e minusculo')else: print(f'{n} nao e minusculo') if n.isprintable(): print(f'{n} e um termo imprimivel')else: print(f'{n} nao e um termo imprimivel')if n.isspace(): print(f'{n} e um espaco vazio')else: print(f'{n} nao e um espaco vazio')

Uma coisa nao tao positiva que as vezes me acomete e que na preocupacao de nao fazer julgamentos precoces sobre o que outra pessoa sabe ou sabe, e em um preciosismo pessoal meu de querer explicar tudo tambem a partir de informacoes claras e seguindo um crescendo, eu acho que acabo indo para uma distancia desnecessaria. E nessa busca de explicar o universo partindo dos seus pontos mais fundamentais a gente acaba descobrindo que precisa de mais tempo do que o universo tem para dar. Sempre da para ir no mais fundamental. Nem sempre a gente e os nossos chegados temos tempo para isso. Descobrir qual e o fundamental minimo viavel e o desafio do qual eu ainda nao tenho claro na cabeca.

Reasons to learn Python:- Python has the most packages/libraries available of any language. And most of those packages are free.- Python is the fastest growing language. While Javascript and Java are still bigger, Python is growing faster.- Python hasn't been corporatized yet like for example Java. While both languages are open source at its core, you have to pay for many Java packages these days and they could costs thousands of Dollars/Euros. Most of the Python packages are still free. Although there are also many free open source packages available for Java as well and especially for Javascript in combination with NodeJS.- Python will get performance improvements of 2x to 5x. They're working on it.- Python has the most AI libraries of any language. If you want to do stuff with AI, then Python is currently your best bet. - Python can be used as both a backend-language for servers, but also as a general scripting language. PHP is a language for server-backends, but it's not suited as a general scripting language.- Python has asynchronicity natively built into it like NodeJS. However it's an option that you can use. So you can use it if you want, but you don't have to.Reasons not to learn Python:- At the moment Python is still one of the slowest languages out there. It's 3 times slower than PHP. However they're working on it.So basically if they would improve the performance of Python, then Python would be hard to beat by any competing language. Granted, Java and C++ would still be many times faster, but if you want to improve performance then you could use Cython for some computational-heavy parts of your code. While it's not a native option, it is an option that allows you to improve performance.

I learned Python back in September 2021, then learned Java in January 2022, then C in January 2023. Python gave me a nice, easy introduction to programming, Java and C gave me a more in-depth understanding of programming (data type declaration, class declaration, memory allocation and pointers, bit manipulation, data structures and algorithms, stacks, queues, linked lists and binary trees, recursion, sorting algorithms, binary search algorithm). Learning Java and C actually improved my python code quality (improved time complexity and space complexity) because I understood how to write clean, efficient code afterwards. A lot of python libraries are written in extremely efficient C code (Python itself and its interpreter is written in C). I was going to move on to learning C++ and UE5, or maybe C# and Unity, but looking at the job prospects right now I decided to pivot to Node.js and React.js since I already know HTML5 CSS3 and JSES6.

import osimport pyttsx3import PyPDF2def transfer(file_input): pdfreader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(open(file_input, 'rb')) speaker = pyttsx3.init() clean_text = '' for page_number in range(len(pdfreader.pages)): text = pdfreader.pages[page_number].extract_text() clean_text = text.strip().replace('n', ' ') print(clean_text) audio_file_name = ''.join([os.path.basename(file_input).split('.')[0], '.mp3']) speaker.save_to_file(clean_text, audio_file_name) speaker.runAndWait()if __name__ == '__main__': pdf = r'Quick Starter Guide.pdf' transfer(pdf)

for everyone getting `ImportError: No module named PIL` READ THIS!:ok so I spent about 48 hours (Took me a long time.. I'm a noob lol) trying to figure out why my system was giving me this. What's happening is, your terminal is running an older version of Python. The PIL module and pip we installed were for Python3.open terminal type in `python --version` it'll probably tell you your default version.now you can run this command >> `alias python=python3` buuuuut we don't wanna do this every time you open the terminal or your VSCode.so you need to create a symlink.to do this you need to find out where your Python3 is actually located.open a terminal and type in `ls -l /usr/local/bin/python*`locate any of the lines that say python and the version number. Mines was `3.11` yours could be different at the time you read this.next you run `ln -s -f /usr/local/bin/python3.11 /usr/local/bin/python`. You might say `But this didn't work for me either :(` that's fine...Run it as admin by adding sudo to the front. `sudo ln -s -f /usr/local/bin/python3.11 /usr/local/bin/python`It'll require your password and BOOM, complete. Now we can go back to this tutorial LMAO.You may need to run this in VSCode as well. Then restart and type `python --version`. It should give you the current version you have.LIKE this comment if it helped and maybe he can Pin it for others that struggled like me.Happy coding.

Quick note for those who may get confused (like I did): the YouTube script won't download 4K video - it won't even download 1080p. Due to YouTube's use of the DASH protocol for higher resolutions, the max resolution that this script can handle is 720p. DASH downloads audio and video separately and you need to post-process to combine them, using something like ffmpeg.

One of the biggest ones is not realizing that mutable objects are always treated as references when passed as arguments to functions. I cannot count how many times my coworkers passed a mutable object to a function, modified that object within the function, and then _returned_ that object, not realizing that the object passed was already modified. And often they would write the script with the assumption that the original passed object didn't change, and things would go wrong without them realizing.

Hey Tim,My friend is using your videos to learn about programming.I like your patient and thorough explanations.One problem I've noticed is that since he is new, he doesn't know much, and so if he doesn't understand what you're doing, he just does it anyway and doesn't really investigate further. Sometimes I will take a look at what he's up to, and ask him why he did it a certain way, and he doesn't know. I know that, of course, it's a long journey to learn to program, and rarely will you understand every step you take along the way. It takes time and practice and patience.Anyway I just wanted to point out that the way you use a nested for loop at 23:25 to fill your list is inefficient and poor coding practice. For loops are more CPU expensive than multiplication. For a small program like this, the difference is negligible, but I still believe it's best to start with the right way to do things, and only use lazier methods as little as possible.You basically do this:list = [ ]for key, value in dictionary: for _ in range(value): list.append(key)But a much better way to do this is:list = [ ]for key, value in dictionary: list += key * valueI don't feel this is substantially more confusing for a new programmer, and it teaches them better programming habits.Thanks again for your videos!

For me starting low from assembly and C/C++ was the best. As for assembler I can really recommend Vlad Pirogov `Assembly programming master book`. I am electronic/computer engineer so complex maths came in packet , with statistic, queuing theory, probability and calculus as every day life. If not for microcontrollers and VHDL implementation, then for electrotechnology, analogue electronics, DSP or even networking/communication protocols. I also got quite good knowledge on GCC and OS as required for some embedded stuff and writing drivers. I recommend everyone to got their hands on books like `Operation System concepts` or `Understanding Linux kernel`.Also get your hands on understanding some database concepts like `The relational model for data base management.` Off course then I picked up Python, JAva and JS. As a hobby I decided I'll pick up HTML and CSS, and in week time I was able to create satisfying looking front ends. Most people when they talk today about software engineering or Devs, means web developers. For me it was always a passion and always treated it that way. I wouldn't change a bit, and I can agree with the author that from simply CS or software engineering perspective it is really hard to apply C to some meaningful projects, but for engineers it will actually teach you to understand hardware and logic like nothing else. Then when you will learn C++ you will really appreciate OOP concept. And when you know C you will understand and utilize Python to its full potential. I also did some programming in logic which not many people use today. If you know more than one programming paradigm, you will be better at solving problems and designing solutions. Off course if you wanna get job as software dev, I do not recommend you going through all that. If however you are passionate about computers and programming, consider at some stage gaining at least basic knowledge of mentioned topics and build some projects. Remember guys that `engineering is build to learn, where science is learn to build.`No project is stupid or small, or meaningless. It all depends on application and what you want to achieve. Whole world today from software to hardware is business driven and all of it is used to deliver business value. There is nothing wrong with that, but try to find passion in what you do, and it will also allow you to think in a specific way. One advice I can give to people regardless what path they choose is to start from statically typed language as this will force you to think forward, when designing the solution for specific problem.

I think C++ is the best foundation for a programmer even if you will not use it anywhere:it teaches you how other languages treat variables and code at a low level.For example Javascript, even if it's a very hight level language, still uses pointers for object; If you are aware of how pointers work from C++ you will understand why your code is not functioning or how to optimize memory or your code.Java is good as a teaching language but let's be honest, it's too clumbersome to be used daily and it's surpassed in most use cases today.Javascript is a good start (at least ES5) but more object oriented or strict languages, even php, may be better for teaching you Objects and types.
